{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 13:41:18.576573", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary of Network Health\\n- Overall routing and reachability look healthy. Hosts in access subnets can reach the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) with low latency and zero packet loss.\\n- Abnormal behavior is isolated to the DNS server (10.200.0.2): all nodes experience a consistent ~1 second added RTT to/from the DNS server, which translates into ~1 second added delay on each DNS lookup.\\n\\nKey Observations and Evidence\\n1) End-to-end reachability\\n- Hosts to web servers: Normal latency\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_0: 1.8–3.5 ms, 0% loss\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_0: 3.1–4.8 ms, 0% loss\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer: 1.4–4.3 ms, 0% loss\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> load_balancer: 2.0–4.6 ms, 0% loss\\n- To/from DNS server: Deterministic ~1 second RTT\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server: ~1003–1004 ms, 0% loss\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server: ~1002–1004 ms, 0% loss\\n  - dhcp_server -> dns_server: ~1001–1007 ms, 0% loss\\n  - dns_server -> web_server_1: ~1000–1061 ms, 0% loss\\n- No loss was observed in any tested path.\\n\\n2) Application-level timing (curl)\\n- From both hosts, HTTP to web servers via DNS names shows ~1.0 s name lookup time, then normal TCP connect and HTTP TTFB thereafter:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> http://web0.local and http://web99.local:\\n    - name lookup ~1.00–1.01 s\\n    - connect ~1.01 s (i.e., ~5–10 ms after DNS completes)\\n    - starttransfer ~1.28–1.52 s (i.e., ~0.27–0.51 s after TCP connect)\\n    - total ~2.08–2.33 s\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 results are similar, with one outlier run but same pattern overall.\\n- Interpretation: The ~1 second name lookup delay dominates page load time; the subsequent TCP/HTTP phases are consistent with low-latency LAN conditions.\\n\\n3) Device/interface inspection\\n- dns_server eth0:\\n  - tc qdisc show dev eth0: qdisc netem 805b: root refcnt 2 limit 1000 delay 1s\\n  - This explicitly introduces a 1 second delay on all egress traffic from dns_server eth0, which explains the ~1 second additional RTT observed from all peers when communicating with the DNS server.\\n- Other servers (samples checked):\\n  - dhcp_server: normal fq_codel on eth0, no netem\\n  - web_server_0: normal fq_codel on eth0, no netem\\n  - load_balancer: normal fq_codel on eth0/eth1, no netem\\n\\nAnomaly Detection\\n- Yes, there is a clear anomaly: a consistent ~1 second latency affecting only traffic to/from the DNS server (10.200.0.2).\\n\\nFault Localization\\n- The issue is localized to the DNS server host, specifically its eth0 interface.\\n- Evidence: tc qdisc on dns_server eth0 shows a netem delay of 1 second; no similar shapers are present on other tested nodes.\\n\\nRoot Cause Identification\\n- Root cause: An intentional traffic control configuration (netem qdisc) on dns_server eth0 introducing a 1 second egress delay.\\n- Impact: Every DNS query to the local DNS server incurs ~1 second extra delay, inflating web requests that rely on DNS by ~1 second per uncached lookup. All other services accessed by IP remain performant.\\n\\nAdditional Notes\\n- OSPF routing and general IP connectivity appear normal: low intra-DC latencies, zero packet loss, and correct reachability to the server farm (including web servers and load balancer).\\n- DNS service itself is functioning (name resolution succeeds), but end-to-end response times are dominated by the artificial delay on the DNS server’s interface., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='7ee27371-3b31-42c4-82f0-cf3f27bb1564'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
